Part 4: Implement Storage Lifecycle Strategies (Cost Control)

Step 4.1: Create Data Lifecycle Manager (DLM) Policy
bash

# AWS Console → EC2 → Lifecycle Manager (under Elastic Block Store)
# Click "Create lifecycle policy"

Field	Value
Policy type	EBS snapshot policy
Description	Migration-Demo-Snapshot-Retention
Target resource	Snapshot
Target tags	MigrationPhase=Source-Image
Schedule name	Migration-Backup-Retention
Retention type	Age-based
Retain snapshots for	90 days
Cross-region copy	Disable
Tags	CostCenter=Migration-Demo

What this accomplishes: Automatically deletes snapshots after 90 days, preventing orphaned resources from incurring ongoing costs.

Step 4.2: Create S3 Lifecycle Rules (if applicable)
bash

# AWS Console → S3 → Select your bucket → Management tab
# Click "Create lifecycle rule"

Field	Value
Rule name	Data-Tiering-Strategy
Scope	Apply to all objects
Transitions:	
30 days	Move to Standard-IA
90 days	Move to Glacier Instant Retrieval
Expiration:	
365 days	Permanently delete

What this accomplishes: Automatically moves data to cheaper storage as it ages, optimizing long-term storage costs.

Step 4.3: Create CloudWatch Alerts for Cost Monitoring (Optional)
bash

# AWS Console → CloudWatch → Billing → Create alarm

Set alerts for when monthly charges exceed a threshold.
Part 5: Clean Up and Optimization

Step 5.1: Deregister Source AMI After Migration
bash

# AWS Console → EC2 → AMIs → Owned by me
# Select Migration-Demo-AMI-v1
# Actions → Deregister AMI → Confirm

Why: Deregistering prevents charges for stored AMI while snapshots remain for relaunch if needed.

Step 5.2: Verify DLM Policy is Active
bash

# AWS Console → EC2 → Lifecycle Manager
# Confirm policy shows "Active" status
# Check "Policy summary" for target resources

Step 5.3: Test Snapshot Retention (Simulated)
bash

# AWS Console → EC2 → Snapshots → Owned by me
# Note creation dates of migration-related snapshots
# DLM will automatically delete after 90 days

Step 5.4: Final Cleanup (When Demo Complete)
bash

# Terminate both instances
# AWS Console → EC2 → Instances → Select both → Instance state → Terminate

# Delete manual snapshots if any remain
# AWS Console → EC2 → Snapshots → Select → Actions → Delete

# Delete DLM policy if no longer needed
# AWS Console → EC2 → Lifecycle Manager → Select → Delete

